{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01YPa8UtYKnLaaNnoez9uc91","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete understanding. Let me provide my final diagnosis:\n\n---\n\n**ROOT CAUSE:** `libyara/parser.c:733` — In the `yr_parser_reduce_rule_declaration_phase_1()` function, when checking for duplicate identifiers in the `objects_table` (which stores variables), the code passes `compiler->current_namespace->name` as the namespace parameter. However, variables are stored globally with `NULL` as the namespace, not per-namespace. This causes the duplicate check to only look within the current namespace, allowing a rule named \"test\" to be created even when a global variable named \"test\" already exists.\n\n**LOCAL FIX:** Change line 733 in `libyara/parser.c` from:\n```c\ncompiler->current_namespace->name) != NULL)\n```\nto:\n```c\nNULL) != NULL)\n```\n\nThis single character change (removing `compiler->current_namespace->name` and replacing with `NULL`) fixes the bug. The lookup for the `objects_table` on line 733 must use `NULL` to match how variables are actually stored (globally), while the lookup for `rules_table` on line 729 correctly uses `compiler->current_namespace->name` since rules are stored per-namespace.\n\n**GLOBAL FIX:** The structural issue is that the codebase mixes global and namespace-scoped storage in the `objects_table` without clear documentation:\n- Variables/external objects are stored globally (`NULL` namespace)\n- Module imports are stored per-namespace\n- The bug occurred because someone forgot this distinction when modifying the duplicate-checking code\n\nTo prevent this class of bug: (1) Document and enforce that duplicate checks must match the storage scope of each object type, (2) Add semantic checks or assertions that verify lookups use the correct namespace parameter, (3) Maintain test coverage like `test_issue_920()` that verifies duplicate detection a